                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>5</watches>
                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="67915" author="jhammond" created="Sat, 28 Sep 2013 17:40:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I manually verified that this works on today&apos;s master (lustre-2.4.93-2.6.32_358.18.1.el6_lustre.gdadfda6.x86_64_ga217228.x86_64) but it would be good to add a sanity test so that we don&apos;t regress on this.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="67914" author="johann" created="Sat, 28 Sep 2013 16:44:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;So the actual situation is that opening_by_fid() a volatile file on a different client works just fine currently. Jinshan just threatened to remove this capability.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After further discussions, we all agreed that this functionality is required for parallel restore and we will just leave it in.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="67912" author="adilger" created="Sat, 28 Sep 2013 06:34:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In upcoming kernel versions, they will also gain the concept of a volatile file and also the ability to link it to the namespace using flink_at() or similar, so it doesn&apos;t seem so unlikely that these files will be seen in normal usage. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="67910" author="jay" created="Sat, 28 Sep 2013 03:28:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Actually it&apos;s working now because we don&apos;t set the DEAD_OBJ on volatile files yet. I think we should have set it to make volatile file look more like unlinked file otherwise we still can access volatile from .lustre/fid path. If they strongly objected to, we can simply not fix it.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
